snippet.textDisplay:
The real comparison for a machine like this isn’t the best Windows alternative at the same price, it’s the premium Chromebooks and new or Apple-refurbished iPad Air and iPad Pro. In terms of what the average buyer who would even be considering the dated MBA, those options fill the same particular design and usage criteria arguably better with their more phone-like instant-on and streamlined user experience.

That’s why my Pixelbook is still what ends up in my bag 98% of the time. Despite launching end of 2017, I still have people ask me about it. Mac-level build quality and design, excellent keyboard and perfect matte glass trackpad, high res display is crisp, hinge design is tuned exactly right, and even the pen works great (though it really need a better storage solution).

snippet.textDisplay:
I have a gripe, and it isn't particular to LTT at all, but: Why do we honestly care about deck flex on a laptop? I get the point IF the laptop is so inexplicably squishy that it bounces every time you type on it, but at what point in your daily use of a laptop do you take it out of the bag, put a hand on either side of it, and actively try to twist it, as if you were trying to break it? Do you type with all the force and body weight your seated torso can apply? Do you use the keyboard deck as a place to aggressively rest your elbows?


The same thing applies to headphones. I understand that portable ones need to display a strong resilience to damage---from being stuffed into backpacks, dropped on public transit, etc---but I have seen countless reviews where people take headphones that are CLEARLY meant to be used at home (open backed, 8 foot cables and so on) and just twist the crap out of the entire headset in order to demonstrate their toughness. What? Why?? What is also incredibly silly is that some reviews will complain about headsets in general being too heavy, then immediately bemoan the use of plastic in place of metal. The headsets that are intended for home use should be comfortable, lightweight, and sound good. That's IT. That's ALL. I understand some folks have kids that can "mishandle" electronics gear, but if that's the case, I'd be much more worried about my monitor, or my computer case---many of which are tempered GLASS that are celebrated by the same folks who are strongman-style twisting headsets like pretzels and jumping up and down on laptop keyboards to demonstrate how resilient they are.


Just stop with the deck flex bit, aight? It feels like you don't have enough actual material to critique, so you throw this in there like it is a substantial part of the decision process. I have never once took a potential laptop purchase and put my entire upper body weight on the thing to see how much it moves. That's silly.

snippet.textDisplay:
I’ve defended Linus in Mac-related discussions before. I think he really knows his stuff, I’ve learned a lot from him, and I enjoy his videos. But here’s the thing.

It’s quite silly that there needs to be a neverending stream of comments like “I know it has a pretty logo on the side,” implying that somehow people who buy Apple’s products are just completely stupid and incapable of making an informed decision like everyone else. I know plenty of extremely intelligent people who love Apple products. Linus seems to think he needs to teach Apple users about computers, because somehow that would prove to them they’re not worth buying.

I built my own PC, running Windows with a 9900KS. I know all about that world, and it’s great. BUT, I still love Apple products too.

Linus gives me the impression that he’s just trying to discredit Apple in every one of his videos about their products. He gives them props for certain things, but in this video he openly admits he was looking for a way to discredit the Air, and is happy when he finds it. That’s really quite biased. He has a very specific way that he thinks about computers, and he can’t seem to see an Apple computer outside that lense and really understand the value they have for their most loyal users. As someone who knows computers more than most people, I think that’s a failure on his part.

snippet.textDisplay:
A laptop is supposed to have long battery life, a large trackpad that's at least close to the apple trackpad, is lightweight, with a solid hinge design, and has low power usage with a great keyboard. It should also have good passive cooling which is only possible with an aluminium unibody design.

At the moment that's a Macbook Air. If Dell, HP or Acer tried to actually compete with a true unibody instead of making cheap flexing plastic things for the same price and then putting the worst trackpad they could find on it, I'd rather support them, but they don't want to do it, it seems. The only other true option is the Xiaomi Mi Notebook.

Putting an i9 in a laptop is ridiculous. Having a huge 200W power brick to run the underpowered RTX2080 in MXM form is just plain wasteful. Just build a proper high end desktop for performance.

snippet.textDisplay: I have a 2013 MacBook Pro. It was a gift to load up and play back my background music as a one man band performer. Sounds good but otherwise I have no use for it. Blocks most sites I want to look at and it won't download my photos off my phone and I don't want to bother wasting my valuable time spending hours on Google to figure it out. I just use my 8 year old cheapest $250 Toshiba that still works great. I know for a fact most people using Macs spend a lot of time looking up how to use them on Google. If you never had to, well I'm glad for you. In my opinion, regular non tech type people should never buy an Apple computer. I also have an iPad that's just a paperweight because a friend of a friend died without leaving the password and Apple will not believe me without a lawyer and a death certificate with verifiable proof I didn't steal it. I never want an iPhone either. I have a 4 year old free 5.4 inch screen XTE from Metro PCS that I love.
